Predicting Used Cars Prices¶

Predicting used cars prices is one of the classic problems of machine learning models. In this project, we are going to tacke this problem using a dataset from Kaggle. This data set is quite challenging because on the one hand it is has about 440 thousand of rows, and on the other hand it has a lot of categorical data, which makes the task of predicting a continuous variable (the price of the car) a bit difficult.

The data can be found here:

https://www.kaggle.com/austinreese/craigslist-carstrucks-data

By looking at the list of columns, we can anticipate that the following features will not be needed for our analysis:

  • id: unique identifier for the ad
  • url: url of the ad
  • region: if geographical information is required, we can use lat and long
  • region_url: region-specific url of the ad
  • VIN: Vehicle Identification Number (with the Department of Motor Vehicles).
  • image_url: url of the car image associated with the ad
  • county: county of the ad.

We will drop the remaining columns right away. We may drop more columns as we go along.

In [6]:
cols_to_drop = ['id','url','region','region_url','VIN','image_url','county']
vehicles = vehicles_original.drop(columns = cols_to_drop, axis = 1)

Numerical variables¶

There are 4 numerical variables in our dataset: price, year, odometer, lat and long. Let's find the distribution of the first three variables. We'll start with the price variable.

The price variable

In [8]:
plt.hist(vehicles['price'], bins=40, color='red')
plt.xlabel('price')
plt.ylabel('number of ads')
plt.show()

The fact that the x axis extends to 4 billion is clearly wrong. Let's find the minimum and maximum values of the price variable:

In [9]:
print('Minimum price for a car: %d' % vehicles.price.min())
print('Maximum price for a car: %d' % vehicles.price.max())

Minimum price for a car: 0
Maximum price for a car: 3736928711

Let's impose an arbitrary cutoff price of $300,000. The number of records we will lose by dropping cars with a price higher than the cutoff price is:

In [10]:
price_cutoff = 300000
vehicles[vehicles.odometer > price_cutoff].shape[0]
Out[10]:
2800

This represents less than 1% of the total number of ads. Let's drop these records now and drop the distribution of prices again:

In [11]:
vehicles = vehicles[vehicles.price<price_cutoff]
plt.hist(vehicles['price'], bins=40, color='red')
plt.xlabel('price')
plt.ylabel('number of ads')
plt.show()

Let's find out how many cars have a list price of zero dollars:

In [12]:
print('Number of ads with a price of zero dollars: %d' % vehicles[vehicles.price==0].shape[0])

Number of ads with a price of zero dollars: 34089

We shall drop these ads from our data set, because it doesn't make sense to use these records for a model predicting car prices:

In [13]:
vehicles = vehicles[vehicles.price>0]

We also see that there are 130 ads for 2022 models. We will assume that this is not a typo and keep the model year as 2022 for these ads.

The first thing we notice is that an odometer of zero is not necessarily associated with a brand new car (unless we consider that records for cars from 1969 or 1961 are still brand new). Also, by looking at the condition, title status and description columns we can see that these are not necessarily cars that have been in an accident. Let's find how many records with a zero odometer reading thre are:

print('Number of records with an odometer reading of zero: %d' % vehicles[vehicles.odometer == 0].shape[0])

Given the small total number of these records, we will make the decision to delete them from our dataset:

In [23]:
vehicles = vehicles[vehicles.odometer > 0]

We will not utilize the remaining two numerical variables (lat and long) and choose to instead use the state categorical variable for geographical data if needed. The logic behind this is the realization that the price of a car will likely depend on the state, but not on finer granularities of geographic location described by longitude and latitude. We therefore will drop the long and lat columns:

In [24]:
vehicles = vehicles.drop(columns=['long','lat'], axis = 1)

A Google search on the types of car transmission reveals that there are three types: automatic, manual and CVT (continuously variable transmission), so we'll assume that this is what the label 'other' represents. We see that there are 1585 NaN values. We shall replace these with automatic, since its the most frequent value (mode) of the distribution:

More EDA¶

Let's probe if there are any correlation between price and the other two numerical variables of interest, odometer and car age by computing the correlation matrix:

In [57]:
correlation_matrix = vehicles.corr()
correlation_matrix
Out[57]:
price year odometer car_age
price 1.000000 0.345926 -0.474380 -0.345926
year 0.345926 1.000000 -0.343078 -1.000000
odometer -0.474380 -0.343078 1.000000 0.343078
car_age -0.345926 -1.000000 0.343078 1.000000

Findings:

  • There is a negative correlation of -0.47 between odometer and price, which makes sense: cars with more mileage tend to cost less.
  • There is also a negative correlation of -0.35 between the car age and price, which also makes sense: older cars tend to cost less.
  • On a side note: there is a positive correlation of 0.34 between the car age and the odometer: older cars tend to have more mileage.

We see that most manufacturers have many ads with prices that lie in the outlier region. Let's write a custome function to try to remove these outliers from our data.

In [61]:
def IQR(dist):
    # This is the interquantile range of a distribution dist
    return np.percentile(dist,75) - np.percentile(dist,25)

def upper_cutoff(dist):
    # This is the upper cutoff of a distribution dist
    # byond which a data point is considered to be an outlier
    
    return np.percentile(dist, 75) + 1.5*IQR(dist)

def remove_price_outliers(manufacturer):

    # First, isolate the price column corresponding to a given manufacturer 
    df = vehicles[vehicles['manufacturer']==manufacturer].loc[:,['price']]
    
    # This is to detect the outliers using the z-score
    # z_scores = zscore(df)
    # abs_z_scores = np.abs(z_scores)
    # filtered_entries = (abs_z_scores < 2)
    
    # This is the upper cutoff to detect outliers
    cutoff = upper_cutoff(df)
    
    # Create a filter
    filtered_entries = (df['price'] < cutoff)
    
    # Apply the filer
    df = df[filtered_entries]
        
    return df

Having cleaned the outliers in the price attribute, let's make a first attempt at building a linear regression model to predict the price of cars for this particular model. This will be done next.

Linear Regression Model¶

We now want to prepare our data for linear regression. We'll use a pipeline for numerical features (odometer and car_age) where we rescale these two variables to be in the (0,1) range:

In [67]:
num_attribs = ['odometer','car_age']
num_pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('min_max_scaler', MinMaxScaler()),
])

For the categorical attributes, we will use a one hot encoder, and wrap a column transformer around the numerical and categorical pipelines:

In [68]:
cat_attribs = ['manufacturer','condition','fuel','title_status','transmission','drive','type','state']
full_pipeline = ColumnTransformer([
    ('num', num_pipeline, num_attribs),
    ('cat', OneHotEncoder(), cat_attribs),
])

We now apply our full pipeline to transform the data frame vehicles2 (with data restricted to one manufacturer only):

In [69]:
vehicles_prepared = full_pipeline.fit_transform(vehicles2)

The labels are given by the price column of the vehicles2 data frame:

In [70]:
labels = vehicles2['price']

Let's define a linear regression model and fit it to the prepared features and associated labels:

In [71]:
lin_reg = LinearRegression()
lin_reg.fit(vehicles_prepared, labels)

This result indicates that the RMSE of the predicted prices is about $62\%$ of the median price of cars for this particular manufacturer, which is of course not satisfying. This underlines the difficulty in doing linear regression when most of the features are categorical.

Fortunately, there is a regression method which is well-suited to the situation at hand with many categorical features. This is what we shall use next.

In [161]:
def remove_odometer_outliers():

    # First, isolate the price column corresponding to a given manufacturer 
    df = vehicles3.loc[:,['odometer']]
    
    # This is to detect the outliers using the z-score
    # z_scores = zscore(df)
    # abs_z_scores = np.abs(z_scores)
    # filtered_entries = (abs_z_scores < 2)
    
    # This is the upper cutoff to detect outliers
    cutoff = upper_cutoff(df)
    
    # Create a filter
    filtered_entries = (df['odometer'] < cutoff)
    
    # Apply the filer
    df = df[filtered_entries]
        
    return df

def remove_car_age_outliers():

    # First, isolate the price column corresponding to a given manufacturer 
    df = vehicles4.loc[:,['car_age']]
    
    # This is to detect the outliers using the z-score
    # z_scores = zscore(df)
    # abs_z_scores = np.abs(z_scores)
    # filtered_entries = (abs_z_scores < 2)
    
    # This is the upper cutoff to detect outliers
    cutoff = upper_cutoff(df)
    
    # Create a filter
    filtered_entries = (df['car_age'] < cutoff)
    
    # Apply the filer
    df = df[filtered_entries]
        
    return df

Conclusion¶

Despite our best efforts, we weren't able to achieve good values of the RMSE in any of the models we built (the best value of RMSE we were able to achieve was 0.28). Like we mentioned before, this underlines the difficulty in building regression models for data sets that have many categorical variables and fewer numerical variables. More work is necessary to drill down the data even further and try to achieve better predictive results. One possibility is to try to use the OLS class from the statsmodels.api package to try to better understand how the different categories affect the regression estimates. This will be the subject of a future project.
